=E2=9C=85 Short Answer

JavaScript=E2=80=99s scope collection is typically implemen= ted as a combination of:

  • Hash tables / dictionaries (maps) =E2=86=92 for fast iden= tifier lookup

  • Linked structure / parent pointers =E2=86=92 so each scop= e knows its parent scope

  • A tree of scopes representing the entire program

So internally, it=E2=80=99s:

A tree of scopes, where each node (scope) contains a map of variable names.

Now let=E2=80=99s go step by step an= d explain the real structure used inside modern JS engines like V8, SpiderM= onkey, and JavaScriptCore.

=E2=9C=85 What Is the Scope Chain? (Simple Definition)

The scope chain is the linked list of all lexical scopes, from the current scope =E2=86=92 its parent =E2=86=92 grandpa= rent =E2=86=92 global scope.

It is the mechanism the JavaScript e= ngine uses to find variables when executing code.

Because JavaScript uses lexical scoping:

  • Every time you create a function or = block {}, a new scope is created.

  • That scope is linked to the scope where it was defined (it= s parent).

  • These links form a chain used for variable lookup.

=E2=9C=94 A tree of scopes (entire program)

=E2=9C=94 A linked list from each scope to its parent

  • A parent pointer to the next outer scope

=F0=9F=94=A5 Important Detail Abo= ut a++ vs ++a

  • Return new value

i deep int RHS LHS in this section=20 "Errors Why does it matter whether we call it LHS or RHS? Because these two types of look-ups behave differently in the circum=E2=80= =90 stance where the variable has not yet been declared (is not found in any consulted scope). Consider: function foo(a) { console.log( a + b ); b =3D a; } foo( 2 ); When the RHS look-up occurs for b the first time, it will not be found. This is said to be an =E2=80=9Cundeclared=E2=80=9D variable, because it is = not found in the scope. If an RHS look-up fails to ever find a variable, anywhere in the nested scopes, this results in a ReferenceError being thrown by the engine. It=E2=80=99s important to note that the error is of the type ReferenceError= . By contrast, if the engine is performing an LHS look-up, and it arrives at the top floor (global scope) without finding it, if the program is not running in =E2=80=9CStrict Mode,=E2=80=9D1 then the global scope will create a new vari=E2=80=90 able of that name in the global scope, and hand it back to Engine. =E2=80=9CNo, there wasn=E2=80=99t one before, but I was helpful and created= one for you.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CStrict Mode,=E2=80=9D which was added in ES5, has a number of diff= erent be=E2=80=90 haviors from normal/relaxed/lazy mode. One such behavior is that it disallows the automatic/implicit global variable creation. In that case, there would be no global scoped variable to hand back from an LHS look-up, and Engine would throw a ReferenceError similarly to the RHS case. Now, if a variable is found for an RHS look-up, but you try to do something with its value that is impossible, such as trying to executeas-fu= nction a nonfunction value, or reference a property on a null or undefined value, then Engine throws a different kind of error, called a TypeError. ReferenceError is scope resolution-failure related, whereas TypeEr ror implies that scope resolution was successful, but that there was an illegal/impossible action attempted against the result." the author just was satisfied write cases but he don't give example by cod= e for understand each case because speking is not complete without exmaples= code !=20 explain each case with code exmaples
